SIMPLE: smack
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Smack
<hw>Smack</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[D. <ets>smak</ets>;
akin to LG. <ets>smack</ets>, <ets>smak</ets>, Dan. <ets>smakke</ets>,
G. <ets>schmacke</ets>, F. <ets>semaque</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>
<def>A small sailing vessel, commonly rigged as a sloop, used chiefly in
the coasting and fishing trade.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smack</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Smack
<hw>Smack</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>smak</ets>, AS.
<ets>ssm<?/c</ets> taste, savor; akin to D. <ets>smaak</ets>, G.
ge<ets>schmack</ets>, OHG. <ets>smac</ets>; cf. Lith. <ets>smagus</ets>
pleasant. Cf. <er>Smack</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Taste or flavor, esp. a slight taste or flavor; savor; tincture;
<as>as, a <ex>smack</ex> of bitter in the medicine</as>. Also used
figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So quickly they have taken a <qex>smack</qex> in covetousness.</q>
<rj><qau>Robynson (More's Utopia).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They felt the <qex>smack</qex> of this world.</q>
<rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small quantity; a taste.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A loud kiss; a buss.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A clamorous
<xex>smack</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A quick, sharp noise, as of the lips when suddenly
separated, or of a whip.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A quick, smart blow; a slap.</def>
<rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smack</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Smack
<hw>Smack</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>As if with a smack or slap.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smack</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Smack
<hw>Smack</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Smacked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Smacking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>smaken</ets> to taste,
have a taste, -- from the noun; cf. AS. <ets>smecan</ets> taste; akin to
D. <ets>smaken</ets>, G. <ets>schmecken</ets>, OHG. <ets>smechen</ets>
to taste, smach<?/n to have a taste (and, derived from the same source,
G. <ets>schmatzen</ets> to smack the lips, to kiss with a sharp noise,
MHG. <ets>smatzen</ets>, <ets>smackzeen</ets>), Icel. <ets>smakka</ets>
to taste, Sw. <ets>smaka</ets>, Dan. <ets>smage</ets>. See 2d
<er>Smack</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To have a smack;
to be tinctured with any particular taste.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To have or exhibit and indication or suggestion of
the presence of any character or quality; to have a taste, or flavor; --
used with <ptcl>of</ptcl>; <as>as, a remark <ex>smacking</ex> of
contempt</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q> All sects, all ages, <qex>smack</qex> of this vice.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To kiss with a close compression of the lips, so as
to make a sound when they separate; to kiss with a sharp noise; to
buss.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make a noise by the separation of the lips after
tasting anything.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smack</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Smack
<hw>Smack</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To kiss with a sharp
noise; to buss.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To open, as the lips, with an inarticulate sound
made by a quick compression and separation of the parts of the mouth; to
make a noise with, as the lips, by separating them in the act of kissing
or after tasting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Drinking off the cup, and <qex>smacking</qex> his lips with an air
of ineffable relish.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make a sharp noise by striking; to crack; <as>as,
to <ex>smack</ex> a whip</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧She <xex>smacks</xex> the
silken thong.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Young.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smack</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Smack
<hw>Smack</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>heroin</er>; -- a slang
term.</def> <mark>[slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smacking</ent>⟦br⟧
